annotation: The French Defense.
The Winawer variation.
A quiet continuation.  5. a3 is the more common move.  5. Bd2 signals white's interest in trading dark square bishops.
Forcing the bishop trade and eyeing d6.
White needs the f-pawn to help secure the center.
Giving up a pawn in order to launch an attack.
A typical break in the French defense.  Black often attacks a white pawn chain at the head as well as at the base of the chain.
Supporting the e-pawn and facilitating the queen's transfer to the kingside via the e1-h4 diagonal.
Black forces the d6 knight's exchange.
To prevent 15. Nb4.
Creating a white square weakness around the king but black has to make some conssession.
Black covers the white square on g6 just in time.
A mistake.  A move such as 18. Kh1 would've been better.
Ouch!
White is a pawn down with diminished attacking chances.
Oops.
A classic clearance sacrifice where the bishop forces black to respond to the check while the queen on a3 is left hanging. 1-0.

The hyper-accelerated dragon Sicilian defense.  The main idea of these lines versus the usual dragon is that black wants to play d5 in one move.  In the regular dragon black plays d6 and then sometimes a later d5 costing an important tempo.
4. Qxd4 is played often enough but I think it isn't as challenging.

The most challenging line in this variation of the Sicilian is 7. Bc4 0-0 8. Bb3.  I don't think 7. Be2 or 7. f3 are too challenging either.  I think some people play this line thinking that they're winning a tempo after 8. e5 but check out the position in just a few moves.
Now the e-pawn is hanging.
White has to spend time defending the pawn on e5.
Which black attacks again.
If 10. Bd4 Qa5 attacks the e5 pawn yet again.
Now the knight is back on f6 and it isn't clear what the pawn on f4 is doing.  white hasn't won a tempo after all.
This leave a backwards e-pawn but it gives black a chance to get castled.
White wants to dominate the dark squares in the center.
I decided to offer to exchange the dark square bishops.  Notice also that the f4 pawn has come under attack.
Creating additional white square weaknesses around white's kingside.
Preventing White from castling kingside.
15. ... Kxg7 was OK but I wanted to reroute the knight.  It did it's job provoking 14. g3.
I dind't consider this sound during the game.

Here's why:  White temporarily wins a rook and 2 pawns for two pieces.  Normally that's considered fair compensation.  However White's king is going to get stuck in the center and black is going to win a pawn back.  Two pieces are usually better than a rook and pawn.
The only move.
A double attack on the g1 rook and on b2.  The try 21. Qxe7 fails to 21. ...Re8 pinning the queen.
Oops.  Overlooking that the rook on g1 is hanging.
The French Defense. The idea is to play d5 challenging White's e-pawn. But my opponent didn't play the main variation.
I don't play this anymore but the idea is to play Nd2 and keep the pawn on e4 if Black plays d5.
Not a normal move. 2... d5 is the most common move here.
I want to prep for a pawn storm on the kingside in case Black castles there.
A better idea is to play 4...c5 before developing the knight there because now I can control d4 with 5. c3.
An odd developing square because that knight does not have any active purpose there.
Planning g4 whenever Black castles. But Black may be afraid to castle there if I play it too early.
I'm threatening g5 winning the misplaced knight.
Gives the knight the escape square f7.
I thought I was being too hasty. I should've continued the attack slower and safer.
Although I have a strong centre I'm lacking in development from moving too many pawns and my kingside is overextended.
Now the position becomes more like a French structure but where Black hasn't played c5.
I wasn't sure exactly what the reason for this was.
This move was also odd to me.
I plan to castle queenside where I have pawns to cover me.
Black keeps making odd moves here.
I thought Be3 was a better place for my bishop where it doesn't sit on the open f-file.
Black has made 4 odd moves in a row and I should've been winning except I made a huge blunder here getting into a lost position.

15. Nbd2?? is totally losing because I hang the bishop. This is a common mistake in correspondence chess because a lot of times players will go to a game they haven't looked at for a few days and make a move without checking the position for hanging pieces or threats.
I am totally lost in this position but miraculously I came back and won. You're probably wondering how that happened in a position like this.
Usually the best way to try for a swindling desperate attack is to attack the king. I move my knight so that I can reach the good g6 square with a better chance to swindle Black.

My position looks terrible! A lot of my pieces are on the back rank and Black has control of the f-file. I thought for sure I would lose but I didn't resign because there were so many pieces on the board and material advantages are only useful with fewer pieces on the board.
Although trading bishops would take away Black's bishop pair I must avoid trading my active pieces if I want to swindle Black.
Black probably didn't think very much on that move. He probably thought I had no chance to win because I'm down a piece and just expected the game to win itself.
Why is Black retreating? He must think I'm going to resign any move now.

In just a few moves the position has changed. Now I'm the one with all the active mobil pieces and Black is the one with the cramped position. And material advantages are less useful in cramped positions so I'm not really "totally" losing. Just losing.
I challenge the f-file.
Another random move. Black thinks there is no way he could possibly lose but his bad play continued giving me a brilliant swindle I felt very happy about.
Black wants to open up files to my king but he doesn't have very many active pieces there so I am not worried. I have lots of active pieces on the kingside so I should mainly focus there.
I am eyeing the weak g-pawn.

Black just gave me control of the f-file so my chances to swindle Black are increased. Black is probably thinking "why won't this guy just die." And is frustrated that his extra piece isn't helping him much.

I don't care about losing my a-pawn because I'm already down a piece and a pawn won't make much difference. If I take the pawn then Black can attack much faster and I don't have time for my swindling attempt on the kingside.
I am headed for f4 where I attack the weak g-pawn. The key to getting a successful kingside attack is to first attack the pawns.
Another wasted move. Black doesn't want to work for his win and wants it to be handed to him. Black has an attack going on the queenside and should've tried piling his heavy pieces on the b-file.

Taking the a4 pawn just loses a tempo deactivates my bishop and material isn't important to me right now because I am working for a kingside attack. Don't let distractions like that keep you from carrying out your intended plans.
Black is underestimating my swindling chances and thinks anything he does will win because he has an extra piece and pawn.
If Black takes then I will play Qh7  and g6 which gives me a lot more swindling chances than if he doesn't take my knight.
Black is realizing now that I still have chances to win and must neutralize these chances and win with his extra piece in the endgame.
It isn't good to trade when you're down material but Black was threatening both my knights so a trade was forced and trading on f5 solidifies Black's kingside lessening my swindling chances.
Not the best way to trade. My knight on g7 is much more powerful than my knight on h4.
Black probably thought my knight was trapped but if he takes then I can still play Qh7
Black blocks my strong diagonal.
Black should've taken this knight earlier because now my knight is posted on f7 where it cannot be disturbed and controls good squares in Black's camp.
I am trying desperately for a swindling attempt.

A terrible move. If Black doesn't take the pawn and just keeps the knight on f5 then I have no chance to win and Black is up a piece. Black probably greedily took the pawn without a second thought and is amazed that I haven't resigned yet.
Black is in big trouble and may even be losing here but his next move was a definite blunder which hands me a winning position.
Black may have still had a chance I'm not sure but now I am totally winning although I hadn't realized it yet.
The h8-knight is doomed and my crushing attack will eventually eat Black alive.
I hadn't realized my winning position yet until I found the one magical move which saved my game.
Nxd5!! wins and Black has no idea what hit him. His trouble started when he took my h-pawn. Now he must pay the price.
Kd7 was the only other legal move but Nb6  or Bxa4  win Black's queen.
I'm down a piece again but this time my attack is unstoppable.

Kf8 loses after 42. Bxf5 gxf5 43. Rh1!! unstoppably threatening Rh8  which either mates or wins the queen.
But Ke8 is still losing.
Now I can't kill Black's only good defender with Bxf5 but I need to get Black's king back into danger and it gave me a more brilliant win.
Threatening Rh8#
The only way to stop mate is to attempt to block on g8.

Black resigned in this position because he can't stop both my mating threats of Qxf7# and Qg7#.
Although I wasn't pleased with myself blundering a piece I love this game because it shows how I went from being down a piece in a hopelessly lost position to fighting desperately for a brilliantly winning tactical attack and it certainly must've made my opponent feel like crap to lose like this!
Scotch
White has a formidable centre and the doubled c-pawn is not a weakness as it provides open b& d files.
Utilising the open file and preventing Black bishop from developing
Blokade b-pawn and pinning d6 pawn
White has to protect c-pawn and f-pawn so the rook at f1 can move. Ideal square will be g3 which threatens Blacks king as well
Again to prevent Black Bishop movement.
Blacks pawns are blocked and Black  bishop has become a 'bad' one
...axb6(R) will lead to Rxb8(R) entry for the rook to 8th rank
Black avoids it. But d6-pawn loses support from R at d8
take advantage of the pin at d6.
Grab the d6 pawn after exchange at g6. If ....Qf5 then Bd3
do not give up control of open file
Centralize the king as endgame is approaching
echange is all the better for white
Black did not expect en passent
another pawn falls
Laying trap if ...Bd7 then Re7  wins the bishop. If ....Rd8 then Ke3
Black did not fall for the trap. But exchange will favor white as he is two pawns up

Interesting position!. If 35.Bd5 b4! 36.cxb4 cxb4 37.axb4 Bc6!!
Bxc6 is a taboo. If 38Bxc6 a3! and the Black's a-pawn is unstoppable. White's Bishop can not stop a-pawn due to its own pawn at c4.
If White avoids capture by Be6 Black will play Bd7. Any other move black will simply push a-pawn
So White captures the pawn. With 2 pawns up it is a sure win
bringing king to centre for active play
Prevent Black king's advance
h-pawn is unstoppable! 1-0

I am Black. The person playing White was the highest rated person in this tournament. He ended up getting 1st but I like this game because it reminds me I was the only person in the tournament who managed to beat him.
The Benoni Defense. I immidiately challenge White's pawn.

The strongest move. Moves like e3 and c3 are also okay but they're passive and let Black get easy equality.
A worse move option for White is dxc5 which gives Black a slight advantage and then it's White who is fighting for equality.
Also White can play Nf3 which goes into an entirely different opening if he doesn't want to study the Benoni.

I challenge White's pawn again. Forcing him to defend with e4 or c4. Other moves for White aren't good because he moved his d-pawn twice and must keep the pawn on d5 by defending with another pawn. Otherwise the tempi used advancing the d-pawn will be a waste.

This move is the sharpest leading to an unbalanced sharp tactical game while defending with e4 is more dull and drawish. I usually play Nf6 before I play e6 because it avoids the boring line e4 but since I was playing a much better player I wouldn't have minded if he'd played the drawish e4.
I open my e-file I can use after I castle.
This move stops White's pawn from advancing any further although it isn't necessary right now because if he advances I can play Qb6 and his pawn cannot be defended because Bf4 leaves b2 hanging.
Fianchettoing this bishop in the Benoni Defense is very important because I need to add to my control of the central dark squares.
This is a very common position in this opening although I thought Bg4 was better because it trades my passive bishop for White's centre-controlling knight.
White stops Bg4 I should've played it the move earlier.
This bishop develops to d3 to defend the e-pawn.
I am planning to play b5 giving me nice queenside control.
This guy was much higher rated than I was so he knew how to stop my plan.
Bd3 helped defend White's e-pawn.
The only good move I saw.
White playing e5 later could be dangerous.
I like my queen here because it defends my weak d-pawn and there weren't very many other moves in this cramped position.
I was worried about White playing e5 while my queen was in line with his rook. If he plays e5 now then I can play Nh5 attacking the bishop and discovering an attack on his e5-pawn.
This move looked awkward to me. I thought a5 was better because it gains more space on the queenside.
I want to trade because White's actively placed bishop is better than my knight controlling unimportant squares.
If Bh2 then I play Bh6 with tempo and can get a slight initiative after Nf4 blocking White's dark bishop while attacking his light bishop.
I didn't want White to play g4 and g5 with tempo so I stop g5. I also could've played f5 but I didn't feel comfortable going into a complicated position with such a good player.
White wants to play b4 disturbing my strong c-pawn.
I make sure that my pawn has a suitable replacement.
I'm not worried about g5 anymore because now my knight has the h7 retreat square.
A dubious move. The g-pawn doesn't really need a fourth defender.
I was hoping White would take the pawn because Qxf6 forks the knights.
White is claiming the b-file but I can always try to trade rooks and I'll have a passed c-pawn after 21...bxc5.
I thought the position was equal here but White's next move however definitely gives me the upper hand with a nice and clear advantage.
White was probably happy here because defending my g-pawn with queen allows e6-fork and taking on e5 allows Bxg6 and Bxh5. So how did I ever win here?
I can afford to ignore the threat on g6 because I will take advantage of White's exposed king.
White probably underestimated my intended kingside attack because of my rating.
Even though I'm losing material-wise (my rook for his bishop) White's king is exposed and I am threatening Bh3 then mate.
White wants to trade queens because then his king is in less danger and he gets to keep his extra material.
My new threat is Nf3 .
White must free the f2 square to save his queen otherwise Nf3  and White must give up his queen and lose. If White tries to stop Nf3 with Bxh5 then I can simply play g4 blocking the bishop.
If 26. Bxh5 g4 had been played in this position then White would have to play Kf1 and I'd play g3 winning because I'm threatening Bh3  and g2
If Kf1 then Bh3#
White's attempt to save his queen has failed so he resigned here. Plus e8 and c3 are hanging and his king is even more exposed.

bit wierd

normal trade brings knight to the centar

preparing another fianchetto bish gotta b careful

I am White. I played this game in a live tournament where I won a first place trophy with a 5-0 score.
Mostly all of the players in Bakersfield tournaments including me play 1...c5
I usually play c3 instead of Bc4 but I'm the scourge of Bakersfield tournaments and was afraid the players were getting accustomed to my normal openings.

One of several good moves. Other good moves are 2...g6 2...d6 2...e6 and 2...Nf6. 
I play 2...Nf6 because I like the sharp unbalanced battles that arise after 2...Nf6 e5 d5 exf6 dxc4 fxg7 Bxg7 because I am leading in development but my doubled c-pawns could become a weakness.
I need to control d5 as much as possible because in this opening it is common for Black to play e6 Ne7 d5 gaining space in the centre and making my bishop move again.

This move adds to Black's control of the central dark squares and g6 Bg7 does the same. I recommend g6 Bg7 in this position because it aids in castling along with control of the dark squares. The move d6 should only be played if extra control of e5 is needed or if Black needs to develop his queen's bishop.

This is the Grand Prix Attack. I rarely play this opening as White but will if I am playing a low rated player or someone who knows my normal c3 opening. I never studied it so most of my experience came from when I play against this opening as Black.

This move may appear strong to amateurs because Black is clearly dominating the dark squares but he has given me a spot on d5 where I can keep a piece in his territory and he cannot chase it away with a pawn.

5. fxe5? is a bad move even though it gives up an f-pawn for a more important d-pawn it gives Black an open d-file and I need my f-pawn because a common move in this opening is to play f5 gaining space on the kingside and maybe following up with g4 h4 then g5.
So f5 was a good move in this position but I played d3 because I wanted Black to take on f4 giving me a more mobil and better developed position. But f5 was better because Black has usually played g6 stopping f5.
Black should've played g6 which stops f5 but instead allows the f5 move again.

A positional blunder. Much better is f5 followed by g4 and h4 with a strong kingside attack. But I wasn't very experienced playing this opening as White. Here Black should've played Bg4 because after trading on f3 Black has control of d4 giving me complications.
Black wants to defend against my threat of Ng5 by moving a piece to e6 obstructing the bishop's path but Bg4 is a much easier way of doing this and after he trades he should have about equality.
I'm not winning yet but I'm starting to gain a kingside initiative.
Ne6 gives Black an uncomfortable cramped position after Nxf7 Kxf7 f5 because I win the piece back while exposing Black's king.
Nxe6 gives me an f5 tempo plus good control of the light squares because Black's light bishop is gone.
Black stopped the possible f5 plan so now I want to weaken Black's centre pawns to attack.
Black's e-pawns are weak because neither can be protected by pawns.
Not completely neccesary. I wanted to control the f-file with my rook but it does hardly anything for my plan to weaken Black's doubled pawns.
Black wants to gain space on the queenside with b5 disrupting my c-file units.
I don't need any further complications interfering with my plans so this simple move stops Black's intended queenside expansion.
Black needs to castle because I may disturb his king during my quest to win the doubled e-pawns.
I strike the defender of the weak e6-pawn but I am not threatening to win it because Nxd4 Qxd4 is check.
Black wants to defend his weak doubled pawns but he should've taken this opportunity to castle since I'm not threatening to win anything.
If Black wanted his rook on the open d-file then he should've at least castled queenside. Black is wasting valuable time and should be making multi-purpose moves like O-O-O.
I wanted to trade my passive bishop for Black's good knight which takes away some of my queen's squares. Always trade your inactive pieces for your opponent's good defensive pieces.
I wasn't sure why this move was made because it doesn't really do anything to help the position except puts his queen on my king's path.
This is why I wanted Black's knight gone.
Black has waved his right to castle and will soon be punished for leaving his king in the centre.

I couldn't find a better move here. I thought about Rxf6 gxf6 Qg7  Kd6 Qxf6 Re8 Rf5 but the position was too complicated and I already liked mine.
I wanted my king off the queen's diagonal in case I ended up moving my bishop I didn't want any annoying c4  cxd3 threats.

18...Rd6??
A losing blunder immidiately giving me the game.
A temporary sacrifice. Never miss tactics like this that will give you an easy win.
If gxf6 then Qg7  winning the rook but taking either way is still losing.
Black's king must leave the defense of the g7-pawn.
This was the move I calculated when I first sacrificed.

This is how much damage can be done if you don't castle. Here I have an extra bishop and two extra pawns on the kingside with an easy promotion path.
Normally I don't like to annotate games where my opponent blunders and gives me a totally winning position but I like this game because it shows how I saved myself from almost losing.

Qh8  simply wins another pawn.
I was too excited about my winning position to make accurate moves and I had less than 5 minutes on my clock while my opponent had about 7 or 8.

I should've been advancing my pawns instead of threatening an unimportant one. Most of my moves here were split-second decisions with about 3 minutes left. My opponent was moving quickly too hoping to run me out of time.

Here I was annoyed because of Black's annoying threats. And I was already nervous because I was low on time. If I move my rook then it becomes inactive and Black has other annoying ideas like Rb6-b2.
The move I made here doesn't allow any of those complications and instead gives me a simple win which would've otherwise been a long complicated battle with less than 2 minutes on my clock.
I was afraid of losing on time in a complicated position so this move simplifies the game and gives me a game that isn't hard to win with less than 2 minutes.
It is okay to give up material when you already have a material advantage. If it is essential in simplifying the game and giving you an easier more comfortable win.
Now I force a queen trade.
Leading to a simple rook-pawn ending where I have three extra pawns and can win easily despite having less than 2 minutes left.
The next ten moves were made in less than 10 seconds.
My pawn cannot be stopped because it can always be supported by its brother on the h-file.
In rook endings rooks usually belong above the passed pawn instead of below it but it doesn't matter in this position because I have two passed pawns.
My two passed pawns are all I need to win so I couldn't care less about the others.
A last desperate attempt to stop my pawn.
This blockading technique only works against isolated passed pawns.
I could still win easily if I ignore the pawn but since I was in time trouble I just wanted to be safe.
Black should resign now. The rest of his moves were made in about 1 second in an attempt to run me out of time but that won't happen now because I have simplified the game.
38. h7?! doesn't win as fast.
Here I stopped recording my moves because my win is clear and I had less than 1 minute left so I was only focused on mating him before I lost on time.
My preferred opening move.
I was expecting Nc6 or Nf6.
This move put me out of my opening book.
I decided to develop my light squared bishop.

Just what i was hoping for.
The other possibility i was expexting was: 5 ... Nd7 6.Nf5 a6 7.Bd3
I think Qxd7 was the better choice.
Attacking the d6 pawn.
One more attack on the d6 pawn.

Here I looked at exd5Qxd5Qxd5Nxd5 and black seems to be ok. 
I didn't like (for no good reason I must admit) exd5 Qxd5 Qe2  Qe6 Nc3 Qxe2 Nxe2.
So I chose ..
... to defend my e4 pawn and to develop another piece.
That was a mistake. Black didn't see what's coming next.
Threatening to fork king and rook - Nc7.
Clearing the way for the heavy metal! White is winning.
Not the best defence. But even Kc8 Nf5 Qxd1 Rxd1 looks grim for black.

Other alternatives:
1. Ke7 Bg5
2. Ke8 Nc7

This is my match vs. Argentine GM Pablo Zarniki who came to a local university chess club and offered $10 for a game (or 3 games for $20) against a grandmaster! The tables were set up so that he could walk around the 25 or so boards to play against everyone simultaneously making a move and then moving on. So I bought a game and even though I lost easily the memory & lesson was well worth it so I'd like to share it.
The Spanish game (Ruy Lopez)
5. Na5 was a new move for me at the time that is meant to remove White's bishop off the threatning f7 diagonal.
9...Qd7 to prevent the knight from sitting on c6
11...Bxd5? is poor because it opens up the e file for attack against the uncastled king and sets up a key positional advantage.
Overly concerned about white's bishop to g5 12.h6 neglects development.
The key positional advantage being the advanced support square for the knight (a concept that I learned not form a book but as a direct result of this nasty game.)
Black offers a5 in vain hopes of removing the knight away from its ideal home on c6.
Desperate Black sacrafices in hopes of creating a lasting counter-attack.
But it quickly runs out of steam and Black runs out of luck.
Knowing that being a rook & knight up esp. vs. a GM that there isn't much hope and Black resigns.
This move initiates the Winawer  and pratically forces 4.e5
Black has managed to give white doubled pawns but at the cost of a strong center and an attack.
This move prepares 7.Ba6 which exchanges off black's bad bishop which is a good idea in almost any version of the french.
An important idea in the Winawer. As Black either has to demolish his kingside with g6 or play Kf8  giving up the right to castle.
It's unclear where the Bishop should go so maybe the immediate h4 was better.
Threatening h5 which destroys the black kingside. The next move is pratically forced.
This move stops to h5 invasion but has the downside of making white's dark squared bishop incrediblly powerful as any attempt to castle kingside can be quickly met by Bf6.
Releasing the pin and preparing Qa4 which would lock up the entire white queenside. In general in the Winawer you want to prevent the queen from getting to the a4 square.
White decides that moving the black queen again so soon will give white a big attack . White decides on Ne2 because once the black knight goes to f5 white will quickly play Ng3.
White doesn't fear an opposite sides castling as black can make no progress on the white king due to the strong g5 Bishop.
Trying to eliminate the powerful knight.
?! I think this a slight mistake as the f5 outpost is useless after Nxf5. Better was Nce7 when black's queen is threatening Qa4 and the e7 knight adds extra support to his f5 knight.
This move is a sort of waiting move as white wants to see what black will do before deciding on a plan.

?? This move is a serious positional mistake as on e7 the knight can go nowhere useful. The only threat Qa4 can be easily blocked by A4 and white should have the superior game. Much better was Na5 intending Qa4 or Nc4.
Black trys to win a pawn after cxd4 cxd4 Qxc2.
!? An interesting pawn sacrifice which leaves black bound up.
?! A slight mistake as now white keeps black tied up for the rest of the game. Better was Qc4 when it is hard to see anything better than accepting the ending when the position is about level.
A tricky move as the a7 pawn is threatened along with the skewer Rc1. Finally the point of Kh2 is seen as the check along the back rank after as after Rc1 Qxc1 Bxc1 Rxc1  saves black material.
Defending agianst both threats.
Forced . As Qxc8 Qxa7 loses a pawn.
Another  interesting idea is 24. Qb5 as after Qxb5 axb5 leaves all of the black pieces are tied down.
?? A huge mistake as now the attack can finally come. Forced was Ne7 when white has blacked tied up but white still has to work.
! Now the bishop comes into the attack with descisive effect. Probably best for black is Kh7 and Kh6  trying to hold back the white queen  though eventually white will break through.
? This last blunder now leads to forced mate due to the weak black king.
! The key move as now h5 can't be defended and the threats of Qh8 mate Qg7 mate and even Rg3 are imposssible to defend.
Trying to trade pieces and distract white from the mating threats.
Now black is in serious trouble as mate is threatened on h8 along with Rg3 check.
Black's move is a last ditch effort to survive though even after Qh8 Ng8 Rg3 mate can't be avoided

Black resigns as after Kg8  Qg7 mate and after Ke8 Qh8 Ng8 Qxg8 mate. This game is a good game showing how sometimes the best way to refute a gambit is to decline it. If black declined the c2 pawn in this game the endgame would of been about equal but instead he got snared in the attack. Also remember if you have a big attack look for mate before accepting material.
Here is an interesting miniature from the French Classical Variation.  I enter a line where I exchange my queen for three minors and more active piece placement.

More popular is 4. Bg5 intending to trade off Blacks good bishop after 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bxe7.  Here White decides to immediately gain space in the center and develop quickly.  The Black dark-squared bishop will then activate to c5 later in the game helping to pressure d4 the key central square in the French.
White secures his center and gives himself the option of a later f5 springing a kingside attack into motion.  Black has to play energetically on the queenside where his pawns are pointing.
The thematic ...c5 pawn break begins counterplay immediately.
Development has centered around d4 for the last couple of moves here I plan to activate by dark-squared bishop to c5 following the centralization of White's kings knight.

Here White shows his intention to castle kingside.  I think this move is better than 9. Qd2 followed by 10. 0-0-0 as my play is all on the queenside and with the White rook on f1 one tempo earlier White has the opportunity to begin his attack earlier.
Piling up pressure on d4 and hitting b2.

Protecting b2 and preparing to reinforce the center with c3 if necessary.  After 11...Qa5 my pressure on d4 has lessened and White has the two bishops and will attempt to rip open the position to activate them.  Black would then be looking way to passive for my tastes so...
I decide to go all in.
The only real try for an advantage after 12. Bxd4 Qxd4  13. Qxd4 Nxd4 Black is a piece up!

Philidor's defence

logically to prevent 10.b5
so 10.a4 to nullify the a6 support pawn
